LICENSE.md
README.md
     1â†’# color [![](https://github.com/fatih/color/workflows/build/badge.svg)](https://github.com/fatih/color/actions) [![PkgGoDev](https://pkg.go.dev/badge/github.com/fatih/color)](https://pkg.go.dev/github.com/fatih/color)
     2â†’
     3â†’Color lets you use colorized outputs in terms of [ANSI Escape
     4â†’Codes](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ANSI_escape_code#Colors) in Go (Golang). It
     5â†’has support for Windows too! The API can be used in several ways, pick one that
     6â†’suits you.
     7â†’
     8â†’![Color](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/438920/96832689-03b3e000-13f4-11eb-9803-46f4c4de3406.jpg)
     9â†’
    10â†’## Install
    11â†’
    12â†’```
    13â†’go get github.com/fatih/color
    14â†’```
    15â†’
    16â†’## Examples
    17â†’
    18â†’### Standard colors
    19â†’
    20â†’```go
    21â†’// Print with default helper functions
    22â†’color.Cyan("Prints text in cyan.")
    23â†’
    24â†’// A newline will be appended automatically
    25â†’color.Blue("Prints %s in blue.", "text")
    26â†’
    27â†’// These are using the default foreground colors
    28â†’color.Red("We have red")
    29â†’color.Magenta("And many others ..")
    30â†’
    31â†’```
    32â†’
    33â†’### RGB colors
    34â†’
    35â†’If your terminal supports 24-bit colors, you can use RGB color codes.
    36â†’
    37â†’```go
    38â†’color.RGB(255, 128, 0).Println("foreground orange")
    39â†’color.RGB(230, 42, 42).Println("foreground red")
    40â†’
    41â†’color.BgRGB(255, 128, 0).Println("background orange")
    42â†’color.BgRGB(230, 42, 42).Println("background red")
    43â†’```
    44â†’
    45â†’### Mix and reuse colors
    46â†’
    47â†’```go
    48â†’// Create a new color object
    49â†’c := color.New(color.FgCyan).Add(color.Underline)
    50â†’c.Println("Prints cyan text with an underline.")
    51â†’
    52â†’// Or just add them to New()
    53â†’d := color.New(color.FgCyan, color.Bold)
    54â†’d.Printf("This prints bold cyan %s\n", "too!.")
    55â†’
    56â†’// Mix up foreground and background colors, create new mixes!
    57â†’red := color.New(color.FgRed)
    58â†’
    59â†’boldRed := red.Add(color.Bold)
    60â†’boldRed.Println("This will print text in bold red.")
    61â†’
    62â†’whiteBackground := red.Add(color.BgWhite)
    63â†’whiteBackground.Println("Red text with white background.")
    64â†’
    65â†’// Mix with RGB color codes
    66â†’color.RGB(255, 128, 0).AddBgRGB(0, 0, 0).Println("orange with black background")
    67â†’
    68â†’color.BgRGB(255, 128, 0).AddRGB(255, 255, 255).Println("orange background with white foreground")
    69â†’```
    70â†’
    71â†’### Use your own output (io.Writer)
    72â†’
    73â†’```go
    74â†’// Use your own io.Writer output
    75â†’color.New(color.FgBlue).Fprintln(myWriter, "blue color!")
    76â†’
    77â†’blue := color.New(color.FgBlue)
    78â†’blue.Fprint(writer, "This will print text in blue.")
    79â†’```
    80â†’
    81â†’### Custom print functions (PrintFunc)
    82â†’
    83â†’```go
    84â†’// Create a custom print function for convenience
    85â†’red := color.New(color.FgRed).PrintfFunc()
    86â†’red("Warning")
    87â†’red("Error: %s", err)
    88â†’
    89â†’// Mix up multiple attributes
    90â†’notice := color.New(color.Bold, color.FgGreen).PrintlnFunc()
    91â†’notice("Don't forget this...")
    92â†’```
    93â†’
    94â†’### Custom fprint functions (FprintFunc)
    95â†’
    96â†’```go
    97â†’blue := color.New(color.FgBlue).FprintfFunc()
    98â†’blue(myWriter, "important notice: %s", stars)
    99â†’
   100â†’// Mix up with multiple attributes
   101â†’success := color.New(color.Bold, color.FgGreen).FprintlnFunc()
   102â†’success(myWriter, "Don't forget this...")
   103â†’```
   104â†’
   105â†’### Insert into noncolor strings (SprintFunc)
   106â†’
   107â†’```go
   108â†’// Create SprintXxx functions to mix strings with other non-colorized strings:
   109â†’yellow := color.New(color.FgYellow).SprintFunc()
   110â†’red := color.New(color.FgRed).SprintFunc()
   111â†’fmt.Printf("This is a %s and this is %s.\n", yellow("warning"), red("error"))
   112â†’
   113â†’info := color.New(color.FgWhite, color.BgGreen).SprintFunc()
   114â†’fmt.Printf("This %s rocks!\n", info("package"))
   115â†’
   116â†’// Use helper functions
   117â†’fmt.Println("This", color.RedString("warning"), "should be not neglected.")
   118â†’fmt.Printf("%v %v\n", color.GreenString("Info:"), "an important message.")
   119â†’
   120â†’// Windows supported too! Just don't forget to change the output to color.Output
   121â†’fmt.Fprintf(color.Output, "Windows support: %s", color.GreenString("PASS"))
   122â†’```
   123â†’
   124â†’### Plug into existing code
   125â†’
   126â†’```go
   127â†’// Use handy standard colors
   128â†’color.Set(color.FgYellow)
   129â†’
   130â†’fmt.Println("Existing text will now be in yellow")
   131â†’fmt.Printf("This one %s\n", "too")
   132â†’
   133â†’color.Unset() // Don't forget to unset
   134â†’
   135â†’// You can mix up parameters
   136â†’color.Set(color.FgMagenta, color.Bold)
   137â†’defer color.Unset() // Use it in your function
   138â†’
   139â†’fmt.Println("All text will now be bold magenta.")
   140â†’```
   141â†’
   142â†’### Disable/Enable color
   143â†’
   144â†’There might be a case where you want to explicitly disable/enable color output. the 
   145â†’`go-isatty` package will automatically disable color output for non-tty output streams 
   146â†’(for example if the output were piped directly to `less`).
   147â†’
   148â†’The `color` package also disables color output if the [`NO_COLOR`](https://no-color.org) environment
   149â†’variable is set to a non-empty string.
   150â†’
   151â†’`Color` has support to disable/enable colors programmatically both globally and
   152â†’for single color definitions. For example suppose you have a CLI app and a
   153â†’`-no-color` bool flag. You can easily disable the color output with:
   154â†’
   155â†’```go
   156â†’var flagNoColor = flag.Bool("no-color", false, "Disable color output")
   157â†’
   158â†’if *flagNoColor {
   159â†’	color.NoColor = true // disables colorized output
   160â†’}
   161â†’```
   162â†’
   163â†’It also has support for single color definitions (local). You can
   164â†’disable/enable color output on the fly:
   165â†’
   166â†’```go
   167â†’c := color.New(color.FgCyan)
   168â†’c.Println("Prints cyan text")
   169â†’
   170â†’c.DisableColor()
   171â†’c.Println("This is printed without any color")
   172â†’
   173â†’c.EnableColor()
   174â†’c.Println("This prints again cyan...")
   175â†’```
   176â†’
   177â†’## GitHub Actions
   178â†’
   179â†’To output color in GitHub Actions (or other CI systems that support ANSI colors), make sure to set `color.NoColor = false` so that it bypasses the check for non-tty output streams. 
   180â†’
   181â†’
   182â†’## Credits
   183â†’
   184â†’* [Fatih Arslan](https://github.com/fatih)
   185â†’* Windows support via @mattn: [colorable](https://github.com/mattn/go-colorable)
